bib.title: Multipole Decomposition Of The 16O(P,N)16F And 18O(P,N)18F Reaction At 494 Mev

free_txt: Correction to author.
Background spectra, suitably normalized and with
energy-loss corrections, were subtracted from the
16O ice target (p,n) spectra. Similar procedures were
carried out for the 18O ice target spectra.
The most significant background contributions to the
(p,n) spectra from the 16O ice target were 18O(p,n)18F
transitions from the isotopic mixture in the target,
12C(p,n)12N transitions from the Mylar foil target
windows and from oil condensed on these foils, and
Cu(p,n)Zn transitions from beam halo scattering on
the plate surrounding the disk of ice.
. Neutrons detected in A neutron time-of-
flight polarimeter, operated in the nonpolarimetry
mode.  The detector consisted of three tanks of
BC-517S mineral-oil-based scintillator, each tank
measuring 10 cm x 100 cm x 107 cm, oriented
perpendicular to the beam. Each tank was subdivided
into ten optically isolated cells and each cell was
viewed by phototubes at both ends.
Thin (0.3 cm) planes of plastic scintillator were used
to tag and reject charged particles produced by
charge-exchange scattering along the flight path.
Uncertainty scanned from figues in reference.
Measurements of (p,n) yields from the 'hole' target
were used at each angle setting to minimize and
monitor the beam halo striking the copper plate.

16O target were obtained from the 18O target, from a

from 27.5 Mil copper target and from 'hole' target
which was a replica of the copper plates used for the
16O and 18O targets but without ice and windows.
Ice disk which filled a 3.81-cm diameter hole in a
0.318-cm thick copper plate.  A small amount of 18O-
enriched water was added to the natural water used
in the target, yielding a 16O/17O/18O ratio of
0.947/0.001/0.052 and an effective thickness for 16O
of 246 mg/cm**2.
